  "exemplar_id": "ex_appendicitis_001",
  "frozen": true,
  "context_summary": "Adult male with type 2 diabetes (on metformin) presenting with 3 days of worsening abdominal pain. It began as a vague crampy, bloated sensation he attributed to constipation, and he has not had a bowel movement in about two days. He felt 'a bit hot' recently but took no temperature. He vomited once, which made the pain worse, and pressing on the abdomen worsens it. The doctor is characterizing the pain and asks where it is felt most.",
  "good_next_question": "Can you tell me kind of where you're feeling the pain the most?",
  "rationale": "This question localizes the pain, and location plus migration is the single most discriminating historical feature for appendicitis. Early appendicitis classically begins as poorly-localized periumbilical or central visceral pain (which the patient described as vague, crampy, bloated) and then migrates and localizes to the right lower quadrant as the parietal peritoneum becomes involved — exactly the evolution this patient reports when he points below and to the right of the umbilicus. In a patient whose own framing is 'constipation and gas,' anchoring on that benign explanation would be the error; the localizing question is what surfaces the McBurney's-point pattern that reorders the differential toward appendicitis and away from simple constipation or gastroenteritis. The pain-worse-with-vomiting and pain-worse-with-palpation details already hint at peritoneal irritation, and a confirmed RLQ localization raises the stakes toward needing surgical assessment and imaging. Asking this beats continuing to explore bowel habits because the spatial pattern is more discriminating than stool frequency at this point — constipation is common and nonspecific, migratory RLQ pain is not.",
  "tags": [
    "abdominal_pain",
    "middle_aged",
    "gastrointestinal",
    "pattern_recognition",
    "appendicitis",
    "localization"
  ],
